ce:section.ce:para:
The UV–Vis absorption spectrum of CPDs in aqueous solution is exhibited in Fig. 3(c). The absorption band at 280 nm originates from the π → π* transitions relating to CC and CC, while the absorption band at 340 nm originates from the n → π* transitions of the functional groups containing nitrogen and oxygen (Zhu, Meng, et al., 2013). This further confirms the presence of many O- and N- containing functional groups, such as -OH and -NH2, on the surface of CPDs. Furthermore, Fig. 3(d) displays the Tauc plot derived from the UV–Vis spectrum (Note S1). According to the Tauc plot, the CPDs have a band gap (
E g
) of 3.46 eV, confirming their semiconductor characteristics. Fig. 3(e) shows the XPS full spectrum of CPDs, with several typical peaks at 285 eV (C1s), 400 eV (N 1 s) and 532 eV (O1s) (Wang et al., 2015). Meanwhile, Fig. 3(f-h) show the high-resolution C 1 s, N 1 s and O 1 s spectra of CPDs, respectively. The C 1 s spectrum in Fig. 3(f) can be divided into three peaks at 284.8 eV, 286.1 eV, and 288.4 eV, relating to C-C/C=C, C-N/C-O, and C=O/C=N, respectively. The N 1 s spectrum in Fig. 3(g) can also be divided into three peaks, namely 399.8 eV (C-N-C), 400.4 eV (N- (C) 3), and 401.4 eV (NH). The appearance of the N-(C)3 peak further proves the partial carbonization of CPDs. The O 1 s spectrum in Fig. 3(h) displays two peaks at 531.6 and 533.0 eV, corresponding to CO and C-OH/C-O-C, respectively (Lu et al., 2017). In summary, CPDs were successfully prepared, and they possess a distinctive core-shell structure, where the polar groups of the outer shell encircle the carbon core. This core consists of amorphous carbon and contains a small amount of graphene-like crystalline structures.

To examine how CPDs affect the dielectric performances of the composite films, the conductivity ( σ ), dielectric constant (
ε r
), and dielectric loss ( tanδ ) were measured to be a function of frequency at room temperature. Fig. 6(a) shows that the σ of all composite films exhibits good frequency dependence, and the CA/CPDs-1 composite film, with the highest CPDs content, still shows high insulation properties. This suggests that the low σ is beneficial for maintaining a low tanδ in dielectric composite materials.
